{
  "doc_id": "16281",
  "text": "Colorectal carcinoma is one of the most common malignant diseases in the Western countries. Even after successful resection of the primary tumor, about one-third of the patients develop metastases in the liver and lungs [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Metastatic colorectal cancer is associated with a poor prognosis. Although in many clinical studies chemotherapy is administered in combination with different tyrosine kinase inhibitors [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , new approaches for targeted therapies are needed. The antitumoral efficiency of vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) antagonism has already been described [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . VEGF expression correlates with tumor vascularization and therefore tumor growth in colorectal cancer [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Treatment with tyrosine kinase inhibitors leads to apoptosis and tumor shrinking. Generally it is accepted that VEGF binds to its cell surface receptors [Flt-1 (VEGFR1), Flk-1 (VEGFR2) or Flt-4 (VEGFR3)] and regulates angiogenesis by either controlling intercellular endothelial interactions or intracellular tumor cell pathways [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . In the same way neuropilin (NRP) may indirectly mediate effects on tumor progression by affecting angiogenesis or directly through effects on tumor cells [CITATION_13] .",
